3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* smtpd_sasl_glue 3
6/* SUMMARY
7/* Postfix SMTP server, SASL support interface
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* #include "smtpd_sasl_glue.h"
10/*
11/* void smtpd_sasl_state_init(state)
12/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
13/*
14/* void smtpd_sasl_initialize()
15/*
16/* void smtpd_sasl_activate(state, sasl_opts_name, sasl_opts_val)
17/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
18/* const char *sasl_opts_name;
19/* const char *sasl_opts_val;
20/*
21/* char *smtpd_sasl_authenticate(state, sasl_method, init_response)
22/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
23/* const char *sasl_method;
24/* const char *init_response;
25/*
26/* void smtpd_sasl_logout(state)
27/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
28/*
29/* void smtpd_sasl_login(state, sasl_username, sasl_method)
30/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
31/* const char *sasl_username;
32/* const char *sasl_method;
33/*
34/* void smtpd_sasl_deactivate(state)
35/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
36/*
37/* int smtpd_sasl_is_active(state)
38/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
39/*
40/* int smtpd_sasl_set_inactive(state)
41/* SMTPD_STATE *state;
42/* DESCRIPTION
43/* This module encapsulates most of the detail specific to SASL
44/* authentication.
45/*
46/* smtpd_sasl_state_init() performs minimal server state
47/* initialization to support external authentication (e.g.,
48/* XCLIENT) without having to enable SASL in main.cf. This
49/* should always be called at process startup.
50/*
51/* smtpd_sasl_initialize() initializes the SASL library. This
52/* routine should be called once at process start-up. It may
53/* need access to the file system for run-time loading of
54/* plug-in modules. There is no corresponding cleanup routine.
55/*
56/* smtpd_sasl_activate() performs per-connection initialization.
57/* This routine should be called once at the start of every
58/* connection. The sasl_opts_name and sasl_opts_val parameters
59/* are the postfix configuration parameters setting the security
60/* policy of the SASL authentication.
61/*
62/* smtpd_sasl_authenticate() implements the authentication
63/* dialog. The result is zero in case of success, -1 in case
64/* of failure. smtpd_sasl_authenticate() updates the following
65/* state structure members:
66/* .IP sasl_method
67/* The authentication method that was successfully applied.
68/* This member is a null pointer in the absence of successful
69/* authentication.
70/* .IP sasl_username
71/* The username that was successfully authenticated.
72/* This member is a null pointer in the absence of successful
73/* authentication.
74/* .PP
75/* smtpd_sasl_login() records the result of successful external
76/* authentication, i.e. without invoking smtpd_sasl_authenticate(),
77/* but produces an otherwise equivalent result.
78/*
79/* smtpd_sasl_logout() cleans up after smtpd_sasl_authenticate().
80/* This routine exists for the sake of symmetry.
81/*
82/* smtpd_sasl_deactivate() performs per-connection cleanup.
83/* This routine should be called at the end of every connection.
84/*
85/* smtpd_sasl_is_active() is a predicate that returns true
86/* if the SMTP server session state is between smtpd_sasl_activate()
87/* and smtpd_sasl_deactivate().
88/*
89/* smtpd_sasl_set_inactive() initializes the SMTP session
90/* state before the first smtpd_sasl_activate() call.
91/*
92/* Arguments:
93/* .IP state
94/* SMTP session context.
95/* .IP sasl_opts_name
96/* Security options parameter name.
97/* .IP sasl_opts_val
98/* Security options parameter value.
99/* .IP sasl_method
100/* A SASL mechanism name
101/* .IP init_reply
102/* An optional initial client response.
103/* DIAGNOSTICS
104/* All errors are fatal.
105/* LICENSE
106/* .ad
107/* .fi
108/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
109/* AUTHOR(S)
110/* Initial implementation by:
111/* Till Franke
112/* SuSE Rhein/Main AG
113/* 65760 Eschborn, Germany
114/*
115/* Adopted by:
116/* Wietse Venema
117/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
118/* P.O. Box 704
119/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
120/*
121/* Wietse Venema
122/* Google, Inc.
123/* 111 8th Avenue
124/* New York, NY 10011, USA
125/*--*/
126

153#ifdef USE_SASL_AUTH
154
155/*
156 * Silly little macros.
157 */
158#define STR(s) vstring_str(s)
159
160 /*
161 * SASL server implementation handle.
162 */
163static XSASL_SERVER_IMPL *smtpd_sasl_impl;
164
165/* smtpd_sasl_initialize - per-process initialization */
166
167void smtpd_sasl_initialize(void)
168{
169
170 /*
171 * Sanity check.
172 */
173 if (smtpd_sasl_impl)
174 msg_panic("smtpd_sasl_initialize: repeated call");
175
176 /*
177 * Initialize the SASL library.
178 */
179 if ((smtpd_sasl_impl = xsasl_server_init(var_smtpd_sasl_type,
180 var_smtpd_sasl_path)) == 0)
181 msg_fatal("SASL per-process initialization failed");
182
183}
184
185/* smtpd_sasl_activate - per-connection initialization */
186
187void smtpd_sasl_activate(SMTPD_STATE *state, const char *sasl_opts_name,
188 const char *sasl_opts_val)
189{
190 const char *mechanism_list;
191 XSASL_SERVER_CREATE_ARGS create_args;
192 int tls_flag;
193
194 /*
195 * Sanity check.
196 */
197 if (smtpd_sasl_is_active(state))
198 msg_panic("smtpd_sasl_activate: already active");
199
200 /*
201 * Initialize SASL-specific state variables. Use long-lived storage for
202 * base 64 conversion results, rather than local variables, to avoid
203 * memory leaks when a read or write routine returns abnormally after
204 * timeout or I/O error.
205 */
206 state->sasl_reply = vstring_alloc(20);
207 state->sasl_mechanism_list = 0;
208
209 /*
210 * Set up a new server context for this connection.
211 */
212#ifdef USE_TLS
213 tls_flag = state->tls_context != 0;
214#else
215 tls_flag = 0;
216#endif
217#define ADDR_OR_EMPTY(addr, unknown) (strcmp(addr, unknown) ? addr : "")
218#define REALM_OR_NULL(realm) (*(realm) ? (realm) : (char *) 0)
219
220 if ((state->sasl_server =
221 XSASL_SERVER_CREATE(smtpd_sasl_impl, &create_args,
222 stream = state->client,
223 server_addr = (state->dest_addr ?
224 state->dest_addr : ""),
225 client_addr = ADDR_OR_EMPTY(state->addr,
226 CLIENT_ADDR_UNKNOWN),
227 service = var_smtpd_sasl_service,
228 user_realm = REALM_OR_NULL(var_smtpd_sasl_realm),
229 security_options = sasl_opts_val,
230 tls_flag = tls_flag)) == 0)
231 msg_fatal("SASL per-connection initialization failed");
232
233 /*
234 * Get the list of authentication mechanisms.
235 */
236 if ((mechanism_list =
237 xsasl_server_get_mechanism_list(state->sasl_server)) == 0)
238 msg_fatal("no SASL authentication mechanisms");
239 state->sasl_mechanism_list = mystrdup(mechanism_list);
240}
241
242/* smtpd_sasl_state_init - initialize state to allow extern authentication. */
243
244void smtpd_sasl_state_init(SMTPD_STATE *state)
245{
246 /* Initialization to support external authentication (e.g., XCLIENT). */
247 state->sasl_username = 0;
248 state->sasl_method = 0;
249 state->sasl_sender = 0;
250}
251
252/* smtpd_sasl_deactivate - per-connection cleanup */
253
254void smtpd_sasl_deactivate(SMTPD_STATE *state)
255{
256 if (state->sasl_reply) {
257 vstring_free(state->sasl_reply);
258 state->sasl_reply = 0;
259 }
260 if (state->sasl_mechanism_list) {
261 myfree(state->sasl_mechanism_list);
262 state->sasl_mechanism_list = 0;
263 }
264 if (state->sasl_username) {
265 myfree(state->sasl_username);
266 state->sasl_username = 0;
267 }
268 if (state->sasl_method) {
269 myfree(state->sasl_method);
270 state->sasl_method = 0;
271 }
272 if (state->sasl_sender) {
273 myfree(state->sasl_sender);
274 state->sasl_sender = 0;
275 }
276 if (state->sasl_server) {
277 xsasl_server_free(state->sasl_server);
278 state->sasl_server = 0;
279 }
280}
281
282/* smtpd_sasl_authenticate - per-session authentication */
283
284int smtpd_sasl_authenticate(SMTPD_STATE *state,
285 const char *sasl_method,
286 const char *init_response)
287{
288 int status;
289 const char *sasl_username;
290
291 /*
292 * SASL authentication protocol start-up. Process any initial client
293 * response that was sent along in the AUTH command.
294 */
295 for (status = xsasl_server_first(state->sasl_server, sasl_method,
296 init_response, state->sasl_reply);
297 status == XSASL_AUTH_MORE;
298 status = xsasl_server_next(state->sasl_server, STR(state->buffer),
299 state->sasl_reply)) {
300
301 /*
302 * Send a server challenge.
303 */
304 smtpd_chat_reply(state, "334 %s", STR(state->sasl_reply));
305
306 /*
307 * Receive the client response. "*" means that the client gives up.
308 * XXX For now we ignore the fact that an excessively long response
309 * will be chopped into multiple reponses. To handle such responses,
310 * we need to change smtpd_chat_query() so that it returns an error
311 * indication.
312 */
313 smtpd_chat_query(state);
314 if (strcmp(STR(state->buffer), "*") == 0) {
315 msg_warn("%s: SASL %s authentication aborted",
316 state->namaddr, sasl_method);
317 smtpd_chat_reply(state, "501 5.7.0 Authentication aborted");
318 return (-1);
319 }
320 }
321 if (status != XSASL_AUTH_DONE) {
322 msg_warn("%s: SASL %s authentication failed: %s",
323 state->namaddr, sasl_method,
324 STR(state->sasl_reply));
325 /* RFC 4954 Section 6. */
326 if (status == XSASL_AUTH_TEMP)
327 smtpd_chat_reply(state, "454 4.7.0 Temporary authentication failure: %s",
328 STR(state->sasl_reply));
329 else
330 smtpd_chat_reply(state, "535 5.7.8 Error: authentication failed: %s",
331 STR(state->sasl_reply));
332 return (-1);
333 }
334 /* RFC 4954 Section 6. */
335 smtpd_chat_reply(state, "235 2.7.0 Authentication successful");
336 if ((sasl_username = xsasl_server_get_username(state->sasl_server)) == 0)
337 msg_panic("cannot look up the authenticated SASL username");
338 state->sasl_username = mystrdup(sasl_username);
339 printable(state->sasl_username, '?');
340 state->sasl_method = mystrdup(sasl_method);
341 printable(state->sasl_method, '?');
342
343 return (0);
344}
345
346/* smtpd_sasl_logout - clean up after smtpd_sasl_authenticate */
347
348void smtpd_sasl_logout(SMTPD_STATE *state)
349{
350 if (state->sasl_username) {
351 myfree(state->sasl_username);
352 state->sasl_username = 0;
353 }
354 if (state->sasl_method) {
355 myfree(state->sasl_method);
356 state->sasl_method = 0;
357 }
358}
359
360/* smtpd_sasl_login - set login information */
361
362void smtpd_sasl_login(SMTPD_STATE *state, const char *sasl_username,
363 const char *sasl_method)
364{
365 if (state->sasl_username)
366 myfree(state->sasl_username);
367 state->sasl_username = mystrdup(sasl_username);
368 if (state->sasl_method)
369 myfree(state->sasl_method);
370 state->sasl_method = mystrdup(sasl_method);
371}
